4.  Technical  assistance  manager  (international,  36  person-months).  The  technical 
assistance  manager  will  be  responsible  for  managing  PRIF  coordination  office’s  technical 
assistance resources, and will also serve as the deputy coordination office director. The PRIF 
provides a mechanism where government counterparts of the Pacific island countries and PRIF 
partners can apply for support to meet short-term technical assistance needs. The technical 
assistance  mechanism  serves  to  flexibly  and  responsively  strengthen  and  support  PRIF 
partners’ engagement with the Pacific island countries in the infrastructure sector. The manager 
will have demonstrated  
(i)  experience in infrastructure issues in the Pacific, including issues of financing, 
operations and maintenance, and planning and management;  
(ii)  communication and interpersonal skills to facilitate strong working relationships 
with  PRIF  development  partners  and  other  stakeholders  in  a  multicultural 
environment;  
(iii)  activity  management  skills  within  a  developing  country  context,  ideally  with 
experience working with multiple development partners and/or multiple countries;  
(iv)  track record of success in supporting developing country governments to develop 
and detail terms of reference and activity designs;  
(v)  experience commissioning and managing the work of international and national 
technical advisers;  
(vi)  skills in preparing clear and concise program reports and other written material; 
